G owes its notation to the monastery of Gembloux, where it was at one time lodged: ‘the most sovran copy of Gemblau', Bentley calls it.² It belongs now to the Bibliotheque Royale in Brussels (10012), and is assigned to the eleventh century. A very inaccurate collation of it made by Jacobus Susius, was sent by Gifanius to Scaliger, who used it for his second editi0n³ (1600).
